# Deployer AWS Resource Governance

This rule is scoped to Deployer project contexts only. It must not interfere with
non-Deployer repositories. If you are not working in a Deployer/LRAH repository, ignore
this rule entirely.

---

## Section 1 â€” Naming Conventions

All Deployer AWS resource names are derived from three platform identity values
(`account-id`, `env-id`, `name`) resolved at runtime from
`@.cursor/skills/deployer-skills/deployer-platform-steering.md`.

### S3 Naming Formulas

| Resource | Formula |
|----------|---------|
| S3 bucket | `{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}` |
| IAM ReadWrite role | `S3-{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}-ReadWrite` |
| IAM Read role | `S3-{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}-Read` |
| SA role (IRSA) | Read from ConfigMap `sa-role-{account-id}-{env-id}` (not derived from `{name}`) |

### S3 Example (generic placeholders)

Given `name = images`, the resolved names are:
- Bucket: `{account-id}-{env-id}-images`
- ReadWrite role: `S3-{account-id}-{env-id}-images-ReadWrite`
- Read role: `S3-{account-id}-{env-id}-images-Read`

Do not embed real account IDs, environment IDs, or region values in generated
files â€” the skill resolves all values from `deployer-platform-steering.md` at runtime.

### S3 Name Enforcement

If a developer proposes a name that deviates from these formulas, reject it
inline and provide the corrected name using the appropriate formula substitution.
Example: if the developer proposes `my-bucket`, reject and respond with the
correct formula: `{account-id}-{env-id}-my-bucket`.

---

### SQS Naming Formulas

| Resource | Formula |
|----------|---------|
| SQS queue name | `{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}` |
| IAM ReadWrite policy | `SQS-{account-id}-{env-id}-ReadWrite` |
| IAM Read policy | `SQS-{account-id}-{env-id}-Read` |
| Queue URL | `https://sqs.{region}.amazonaws.com/{account-id}/{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}` |
| SA role (IRSA) | Read from ConfigMap `sa-role-{account-id}-{env-id}` (same as S3; not derived from `{name}`) |

> **SQS vs S3 IAM distinction**: SQS policies are environment-scoped, not
> queue-scoped. LRAH automatically creates both `SQS-{account-id}-{env-id}-Read`
> and `SQS-{account-id}-{env-id}-ReadWrite` for the environment and attaches them
> to the SA role. No per-queue IAM selection is required from the developer.

### SQS Queue Name Validation Rules

The logical `{name}` part of the queue name must satisfy all of the following
before the fully-resolved name `{account-id}-{env-id}-{name}` is used:

| Rule | Constraint |
|------|-----------|
| Valid characters | `a-z`, `A-Z`, `0-9`, `-`, `_` only |
| Maximum total length | Fully-resolved name â‰¤ 80 characters (including prefix) |
| Case-sensitive | Queue names are case-sensitive; treat `MyQueue` and `myqueue` as distinct |
| FIFO suffix | FIFO queues must end in `.fifo`; this suffix counts toward the 80-char limit |

### SQS 10-Queue Advisory

Count only **uncommented** `"<name>" : {}` entries inside the `sqs_queues` block
in `main.tf` (lines starting with `#` are excluded). If the count is â‰Ą 9, display:

> "You currently have N queue(s) provisioned. LRAH enforces a maximum of 10 per
> environment. Adding this queue will bring you to N+1."

This is advisory only; do not block provisioning unless the count would exceed 10.

### SQS Name Enforcement

If a developer proposes a queue `{name}` that would produce a non-conforming
fully-resolved name, reject it inline, name the specific violated constraint,
and provide the corrected formula substitution. Example: if the developer
proposes `my queue` (contains a space), reject and respond:

> "Queue names may only contain `a-z`, `A-Z`, `0-9`, `-`, and `_`. Suggested
> name: `my-queue` â†’ resolved as `{account-id}-{env-id}-my-queue`."

